text:
Park Avenue, east side, between 54th and 53rd Streets, showing No. 383, one of the earliest of the modern apartment houses in this section, nearing completion.
Another one will shortly rise alongside it, and one in the block immediately to the South, from 53rd to 52nd Streets, where the Steinway Factory has just been demolished; but the small house on the N.E. corner of 53rd Street will not be replaced till 1924. 1911.

Park ave., east side, south from East 54th to 53rd Streets. The newly erected building shown, is No. 363 Park Ave.

About 1915.

Park Avenue, north from 53rd Street, showing fronts of west side. 1928
Ewing Galloway

Perk Avenue, north on west side, from 53rd to 57th Street; showing the block of small buildings much older than their surroundings. Compare with Ewing Galloway's photographs of Perk Avenue north
from 52nd Street in 1905 and in 1932.
Note construction going on in 53rd street; a branch of the new municipal subway is being tunnelled under 53rd Street.
April 3, 1928.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

The same, showing a view farther north. The block of small old houses from East 53rd to East 54th Streets has been replaced by a one-story

Park Avenue, east side, from 53rd to 55th Streets, seen from a tall roof at Madison Avenue on 52nd Street. On the horizon at the left of the picture may be seen the Hell Gate Bridge.

383 Park Avenue, east side, between E. 53rd and E. 54th Streets, showing newly erected twelve story apartments.
about 1930

A general view of the midtown Manhattan East Side zone in the Queensboro Bridge vicinity (59th Street). The photographer is viewing eastward towards same and its Queens side, from a point over Park Avenue and 53rd Street. The religious structures in the foreground are on Lexington Avenue; the synagogue being at the S.W. corner of 55th Street, and St. Peters German Lutheran Church at the S.E. corner of 54th St. At the East River are the identifiable items, the distinctive River House, the clustered apartment center, Sutton Place, and the units comprising the New York Hospital-Cornell Medical College center.

1931

Wurts Bros., photo
